[SharpLab](https://sharplab.io/#v2:CYLg1APgAgDABFAjAFgNwFgBQUDMCBMcAYgPYlYDeWcNCeAMgJYDOALgDwBCAhgE4B8cHryZs4FOAHMApq1RwAvnAC8cAHbSA7nFEdh/ABQBKDJgVZcBIX3GKgA=).

I suspect whatever serialization tool you&#39;re using is happy writing to private non-readonly fields, but refuses to write to private readonly fields.

In general though, it&#39;s a good idea to only serialize models which were written specifically to be serialized. These models can have properties with public setters.

The important information is in a comment - the serializer is BinaryMessageFormatter used to send/receive messages to MSMQ. This class uses the rather troublesome BinaryFormatter. That class isn&#39;t used a lot because it serializes entire types, including their metadata and *private fields*. 

This means it&#39;s dangerous - it can deserialize anything. It&#39;s fragile - even an internal like a field rename will break deserialization. In fact, there are several SO questions where people have trouble deserializing from one assembly version number to the next. It&#39;ll definitely break with .NET Core for that reason. 

This also means that even exchanging messages between different application versions can be troublesome.

A different serializer should be used, especially if the application is going to migrate to .NET Core. There&#39;s no need to explicitly use a message formatter, one can just serialize to `string` or `byte[]` and send that. 

One option is to use eg Json.NET to generate JSON strings and send them as-is. The resulting string is far less verbose than XML and can be understood by any application. This can be as simple as :

    var body=JsonConvert.SerializeObject(someObject);

and

    var message=JsonConvert.DeserializeObject&lt;MyMessage&gt;(someObject);

Another option is to use [Protobuf.NET](https://github.com/protobuf-net/protobuf-net/wiki/Getting-Started) to serialize to protobuf, a compact serialization format created by Google that&#39;s also understood by all platforms. Protobuf.NET is maintained by StackOverflow programmers so we know it has great support. 

The question [MSMQ and ProtoBuf-Net serialization c#](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/7820913/msmq-and-protobuf-net-serialization-c-sharp) asks just this. The necessary code is just as simple :

```
byte[] body;
using(var ms = new MemoryStream()) {
    Serializer.Serialize(ms, entity);
    body = ms.ToArray();
}
```

